/td><td valign=top bgcolor=d1c3b5 class=headings><font color=#000000>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 122<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/10/02 7:25:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Journal Entry #7: No!</span><hr size=1> Isharra sits at her vanity, her pen flicking furiously over her journal as she writes:<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
NO NO NO NO NO!!<br>
<br>
Forgive me, little book, but I need to see that word and get used to using it more emphatically. NO NO NO NO NO NO NO NO NO NO<br>
<br>
Damn my weaknesses! To the abyss with all the questions in my head! How easily I get sidetracked from my duty. No wonder I frustrate Father. <br>
<br>
I do not want to write all that I have to say, as I think someone has been snooping in my things, though I really have no evidence. I usually keep you close by my side, but the upcoming wedding has kept me so busy that I'd forget my head if it weren't attached. <br>
<br>
But please, little book, remind me not to veer off the path chosen for me. Please, little book, help me to remain strong in my decision. <br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
She slams the cover shut and lifts her eyes to the mirror in front of her. The Lady staring back at her looks frazzled, her cheeks mottled and pink with frustration, and her hair hanging in limp clumps, as if recently wet. The wet greenness of her eyes threatens tears, but Isharra does not cry. She must never show such weakness; she must be strong. She lifts a silvery brush from among the bottles and accesories scattered on the elegant wooden vanity, and pulls it through her raven hair, working out the spots where her wet hair had dried in clumps. When she's finished, she replaces the brush, then calls for Marha, her servant and friend.<br>
<br>
The stout dwarven lady appears in an instant from within Isharra's vast closet, a half-folded garment still in her hands. &quot;Yes, dear?&quot; she says amiably, before dropping the cloth and running to her charge's side. &quot;What is it, Miss? You look terrible!&quot; Marha's wide brow creases with worry as she takes Isharra's arm and tugs her down to feel her forehead. &quot;Well, yer not runnin a fever, Miss, but you sure are pink.&quot;<br>
<br>
Isharra waves off the tiny hands kindly, managing a smile for Marha. &quot;I'm fine, fine, nana. I was going to ask you to fix me a bath, with rose oil for soft skin and essence. Could you do that for me?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Certainly, dear. But sit you down here on the bed until it's all ready. Can I get you some tea or juice, Lady? A biscuit, mayhaps? Do you need a nap?&quot; Marha's dark eyes study Isharra's face, obviously not convinced that all is well. The fat brown braid hanging over her shoulder is laced with gray, more gray each day, it seems.<br>
<br>
Isharra smiles at Marha with love and deep gratitude. &quot;No, nana, I  swear, I'm fine.&quot; <br>
<br>
Marha nods, a brow inching into her forehead to let Isharra know she wasn't convinced. She turns to go, stopping to pick up the dropped garment before opening the tall, blackwood door. <br>
<br>
&quot;Nana! One more thing. Please deliver a message to Gareth. I'd like him to visit me before he rests tonight. I have something to show him. . .&quot; the cleric says softly, her voice trailing off in a whisper. <br>
<br>
Now both brows inch into the dwarf's forehead and she opens her mouth to object, but Isharra holds up her hand pleadingly. &quot;Please, nana. This is very important to me.&quot; Marha's dark eyes bore into the Koada'dal, and Isharra knows her nurse  is reading her heart with the experience of years of love and caregiving. &quot;Please,&quot; Isharra croaks miserably.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Very well, Miss, very well.&quot; <br>
<br>
The door to her chamber thuds to a close, and Isharra shivers, the quiet, empty chamber feeling like a tomb.<br>
<br>
