<br>
 The wrought-iron garden chair upon which she sat was pulled up to a tiny matching table set with wine, fruit, bread, and cheese, and tea for herself. Gareth's chair was still empty after forty minutes of waiting, and she was contemplating leaving when she heard the crisp clack of boots on marble. Gareth strolled onto the terrace, the robes of his station replaced by leather breeches and a loose cotton tunic.  His smile was warm as he approached and scooped her up from the chair into a tight embrace.   <br>
<br>
&quot;Isharra, my love! Sorry I'm late.... you know how it is these days at court. I was meeting with an ambassador from Ak'Anon all day... creepy little folks if you ask me.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Do you smell lilacs?&quot; Isharra asked, sniffing at the air. <br>
<br>
Gareth paused as if caught off guard by the question, then replied smoothly, &quot;Why, of course! I had Dyrak fix my bath with essence of lilac, as I know how fond you are of lilacs.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Roses,&quot; Isharra corrected, her stomach sinking. &quot;But no matter; Tis the thought that counts, so they say,&quot; she said cheerfully, a smile painted on her lips. <br>
<br>
Gareth almost seemed relieved as he turned his attention on the food. They sat and ate, talking about little things: rumors at court, upcoming marriages, funerals, and court affairs. The conversation was pleasant enough, if a bit bland, and by the time they were finished, Isharra had worked up the courage for her next step.<br>
<br>
They were walking through the garden, arm in arm, when Isharra came to a halt. Gareth smiled curiously as she looked up into his eyes. They were blue flecked with gold---they could be loving, she thought, a little too eagerly. <br>
<br>
&quot;Darling, what is it? You look as if you have something to say...&quot; Gareth intoned, stroking her cheek with the backs of his fingertips. He barely finished the sentence when she pulled him downward into a long, slow kiss. His smile was radiant when she pulled away. &quot;So finally you have warmed to me, my sweet! It's about time you came around. I was starting to worry that I was marrying a prude, you know. Perhaps I won't have to take others to my bed after all!&quot; he said teasingly, though the unspoken threat hung in the air between them. <br>
<br>
And as Isharra looked up into his beautiful smiling face, her skin crawled, and the woodenness of their kiss lingered on her lips, sickening her. It would have to do. <br>
<br>
