his long silver hair back from his face.<br>
<br>
Isharra's eyes drifted to the kerchief on his plate. How long had it taken her to finish that pattern? The cranberry baste soaked into the snowy white cloth like blood into a bandage. Isharra's gaze fell back to her own half-eaten meal. &quot;That is all I ask, Gareth. I do not question your honor. I just wish to make sure that once we are wed you stop your ...'nightly pursuits,' or whatever you call it. This is the only thing I ask, and I do not think I am asking too much. I am still a maiden, you know. Females have 'needs' as well, don't you think? But I do not seek any bed but my own, at night, to sleep.&quot;<br>
<br>
Gareth laughed harshly, then abruptly his demeanor changed as he knelt down onto one knee and took her hand. The smooth planes of his face caught the candlelight, making him seem like a dream. Little flames danced within his eyes in time to the candlelight's rhythm. &quot;Isharra, my beautiful love. Of course I will be true to you.&quot; He paused, reaching up to stroke her cheek gently, and his lips curved into a charming, sly smile. &quot;I have an idea that will make us both happy.&quot; His hand moved from her cheek to her shoulder, his touch warm and feather-light. Isharra wanted so much to love him, to trust her heart to him. What beautiful children they would have! But the thought fled in an instant as she felt the strap of her gown being tugged down and Gareth leaned up to kiss her neck, whispering, &quot;Why not end this disagreement now, my love? Let us make our marriage bed tonight. I'll not tell a soul. Then I will not have to go elsewhere for my pleasure, and you will no longer seek an empty bed.&quot; <br>
<br>
His breath was hot on her neck and Isharra trembled, wanting to give in, to seal their marriage secretly and get it over with. But something inside her recoiled and she pushed him away gently, blushing. &quot;No, Gareth. Not yet. Father is still up and about. It would not bode well for your future to anger the general, my sweet,&quot; she said, forcing a smile. <br>
<br>
Gareth's eyes blazed with lust, and, for a moment, she feared he saw through her ruse. His hand burned into her shoulder, and she felt herself stiffen. But then he smiled, a sweet, boyish smile, and touched his lips to her forehead. &quot;How right you are, my love,&quot; he said, brushing his lips through her hair, taking in her scent. &quot;But I can't help but want you. You know that, don't you? No woman in the world is like you. You are my prize, my jewel.&quot; The high elf stood and smiled down at her, fixing her strap with a delicate hand, before cupping her chin. &quot;My sweet, innocent Isharra. I'll not deflower you tonight. You are truly a Lady,&quot; he said, then looked into the dim hallway, calling, &quot;Marha, my cloak, please!&quot;<br>
<br>
Isharra stood, smiling gently up at him through her apprehension. &quot;Do you have to go so soon? We could read together, or perhaps go swimming? It's a lovely night. . .&quot; she began, but his finger touched her lips to silence her. <br>
<br>
&quot;No, my dear. You have stirred up the beast in me. I must go release him before he overpowers me and I spoil you for our wedding night!&quot; He grinned, but Isharra just blinked slowly, stunned. Mistaking her silence, he added, &quot;Yes, there are many mysteries to a man that you will learn one day, but not tonight, my sweet. Tonight you remain a maiden.&quot; <br>
<br>
And before she could respond, he yanked his cloak from Marha's tiny hands, and Isharra thought she heard him say &quot;To Kelethin.&quot; to his servingman as the door closed on his back.<br>
