</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 167<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/18/02 2:27:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Betrayal</span><hr size=1> &quot;Kelethin? Gareth warn't in Kelethin, Lady. Oi'm certain Oi saw 'im at the inn in East Commons.&quot; The grizzled old dwarf's big brown brows caved into his eyes like a rockslide and his lips pursed comically as he stroked his graying beard. &quot;Oi, that was 'im. Oi know'd it was. In fact, he even mentioned yer name to 'is lady friend. Oi' didn't get a good look at eeder of 'em, as the lady was cloaked from head ta toe. Small she war, like one o' them treehuggin elfs, but she warn't dressed like 'un. She war wearin a long velvet cloak, black like the night, and Oi got a quick glimpse of oiled leather armor beneath. They was talkin in some strange tongue, but Oi recognized yer name. Oi tol' Marha here soon's as Oi got back ta Faydwer, knowin how close she war ta ye.&quot;<br>
<br>
Marha's eyes flitted to and fro between Brogdan and Isharra, and her hands were in constant motion in her lap. She shook her head as she listened, cursing under her breath as her brother repeated his news to Isharra. &quot;See? I told you it was important that you hear this, Miss. Praise to the gods that he came to me straightaway. Something's not right here. Always knew that boy was trouble. What in the blazes was your father thinking trying to marry you off to him?&quot; Marha's face was pink, simmering with slow rage as she met Isharra's eyes. Isharra, pale as a maggot and still as a tomb, was Marha's opposite as she digested Brogdan's words. <br>
<br>
&quot;You are sure, little sir? You must be positive, beyond a doubt. You say he was in Teir'Dal form, but how did you recognize him then?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;He warn't that way the whole time, lady. He came that way, but Oi'm a sneaky lil rogue an' Oi managed ta peek inta thar room when the lady opened the door ta leave fer a bit.&quot; At this, he grew uncomfortable, averting his eyes for the comfort of the floor. <br>
<br>
&quot;What is it?&quot; probed Isharra, noting the change. <br>
<br>
Brogdan stroked his beard some more, obviously stalling. A thud to the back of his head got his attention, and Marha smacked him open-palm once more for good measure, exclaiming, &quot;Well, go on now! Tell 'er the rest! No time for pleasantries or saving  feelings!&quot; <br>
<br>
Recovering some of his dignity, Brogdan continued, &quot;Oi knowed it war him cause he warn't dressed when Oi saw 'im, and he warn't in darkie form either. Oi sar his long silver hair, his high elfin face, an' that birthmark on 'is hip. Looked like a great big brown turd stuck on 'im.&quot; Had the story not been so depressing, Isharra would have laughed at how red Brogdan's ears were burning and the way he kept looking everywhere but into her eyes. Brogdan was not known for his manners, but he was certainly doing his best to address the subject delicately, and for that she was appreciative. <br>
<br>
Marha turned to Isharra triumphantly, her arms folded over her chest. &quot;See? Who else would have that birthmark? Brogdan couldn't make <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> that</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> up! You should go to your father at once!&quot; the dwarf said firmly. But Isharra was hardly listening. Her eyes were fixed on the lamp-light as it danced in the breeze wafting through the open window. <br>
<br>
&quot;You said his lady was *like* a wood elf, but I notice you did not say she *was* a wood elf. I feel your choice of words was intentional. Am I correct?&quot;<br>
<br>
Brogdan chewed on his lower lip a moment, but when Marha's hand came up again he blurted, &quot;Oi, yer right, Miss. Oi left out that she warn't wearin' gloves. Oi also left out that the reason Gareth war in darkie form is cause his comp'ny,&quot; he stopped, choosing his words, &quot; .well, she war also... . eh...  in darkie form---but Oi don't think it war magic in her case.&quot; Isharra nodded slowly, maintaining control over her emotions. A dark elven mistress was not so bad; after all, perhaps the mistress was like Cronadan, dark in skin but not in heart. Mayhaps she didn't even know Gareth was to be married. If so, then they were both being played as fools, allies in a strange way. This proved nothing but that Gareth was more tolerant than he let on. It was almost a relief, in a warped way. <br>
<br>
But Brogdan interrupted her thoughts, his voice soft and anxious. &quot;But that ain't all, miss. Oi sar 'em both again.  . .  but this time they war in Neriak.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
