<br>
A feeling of forboding settled in the pit of Isharra's belly as the servants parted nervously, opening a path for her. The movement alerted her father and he lifted his face, his face hard and grim. Isharra heard the jingle of coins falling to the floor as her father stood, holding out a hand to keep her away.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, Isharra. Return to your chamber,&quot; he ordered, his voice cold authority. But Isharra could not take her eyes off of his sleeping gown, or rather the spattering of dark marks covering the front. Though they looked black in the darkness, Isharra could smell the blood and identified it immediately. <br>
<br>
Her lips moved wordlessly as she tried to form the question. &quot;Wh- what is this?&quot; she managed hoarsely, her terrified emerald eyes shifting to the open chest on the floor. <br>
<br>
But before Jaryll could answer, voices filled the night outside the open window. A cry of alarm drifted in with the breeze, and suddenly the door began to shake as someone pounded frantically on it. <br>
<br>
&quot;Master Moonsong! Are you all right!?&quot; came a voice. Jaryll managed to get to the door just in time to prevent it being knocked in. Two Felwithe guards stood outside, worried eyes peering through their helmets. &quot;We heard a ruckus and came to check. There's evil in Felwithe tonight, my Lord.&quot; The guard's eyes drifted to Jaryll's blood-speckled tunic and then  at the mess on the floor. Isharra watched them, stunned, her mind reeling. <br>
<br>
&quot;Evil? What do you mean, man? Speak up!&quot; growled Jaryll, his eyes darting from the guards to the box on the floor. <br>
<br>
Both guards hesitated, looking uncomfortable. &quot;Perhaps we should go someplace private---&quot; he began, but Jaryll cut him off.<br>
<br>
&quot;Speak your mind. There are no children here, sir.&quot; <br>
<br>
The guard shifted his gaze to Isharra for a brief moment then back to the old general. &quot;General Moonsong, Sir, Gareth Crystalbrooke and two of his men have been murdered.&quot; <br>
<br>
Both Isharra's and her father's eyes fell upon the chest in horrified understanding, and Isharra's scream filled the night. <p><a href="http://pub36.ezboard.com/bshadesofgray30856"><img
