<br>
Marha was the one to deliver the news. She entered the hall slowly, her face grim and eyes rimmed in red. Isharra's closest comrades and friends were gathered there, awaiting the urgent news that summoned them. <br>
<br>
&quot;Isharra sent me to you,&quot; said the dwarf, pausing a moment to gather her thoughts. &quot;Her betrothed, Gareth Crystalbrooke, is dead, murdered. It's no secret that she held little love for him; nevertheless the brutality of his murder has torn her heart asunder. She will be in mourning for a time. She asks that you make allowances for her current state of mind. I'm sure you all understand.&quot; The little dwarven handmaid curtsied and hurried away, afraid her emotions would break if she were asked to answer any questions.<br>
<br>
And the news soon spread throughout the land that Isharra's betrothal ended tragically; her hopes of marriage were dead. <p><a href="http://pub36.ezboard.com/bshadesofgray30856"><img
src="http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Sogsig1copy.jpg"></a>

</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 185<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/22/02 12:50:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A Search for Understanding</span><hr size=1> Isharra stood on the hillside above the entrance to Cabilis, gazing down at the Trooper as he made his rounds. She was on a mission, a mission to learn first-hand about the majestic race that built such beautiful monuments all over Kunark. Many called Iksar evil, pointing to the deaths of Norrathian pilgrims as evidence. But how would the Koada'Dal react if the Iksar moved into Faydwer and began to settle, claiming elven land for their own? <br>
<br>
The Trooper had seen her from afar and made it clear that she was not welcome in his city. But she knew that the Iksar were not without honor, and she planned to prove herself to them, to gain access to their rich and glorious history.  So, lifting her mace, she swung it as a goblin outrider scurried by. It's skull splintered under the crushing blow and Isharra winced. curling her lips in distaste. &quot;Sorry,&quot; she whispered, lifting her mace again as a goblin witchdoctor tried to scurry out of her way. CRUNCH. And thus, the priestess-turned-pest control reluctantly continued her messy work within sight of the Iksar capital, hoping they would notice her service to them and allow her to continue her scholarly pursuits within their city. <p><a href="http://pub36.ezboard.com/bshadesofgray30856"><img
src="http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Sogsig1copy.jpg"></a>

</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 195<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/23/02 5:56:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Enslaved</span><hr size=1> Mard was directing his colorful wooden cart along a path in Warsliks Wood, hoping the forest giants would have deeper pockets than the goblins from whence he just came. Mard had friends everywhere, but business had been slow, and the only flesh he had left to sell was a fat dwarf, a lame ogre, and two wasted old humans, both gotten in trade for a half-dead horse in Qeynos. Well, the buyer didn't know it was half-dead, anyway. Business had been slow, mainly because the supply of fresh flesh was low. Too many folks staying too close to home, Mard thought bitterly. <br>
<br>
As his cart approached the massive gate to the giant fort,  Mard noticed a commotion upstream from the path. Two giants stood together arguing in their deep, guttural tongue, gesturing excitedly to something on the ground. His curiosity piqued, Mard approached the pair, calling up a  cheerful hello in their own language. <br>
<br>
The giants turned and greeted their tiny human friend with lopsided, ghastly grins as he came to stand between them, his eyes on the ground at their feet. &quot;It my kill, Mardy, mine!&quot; said the giant called Gargle, and the other one pushed him roughly, shouting, &quot;No, Gargle KS it from me, Mardy! I tried to tell GM, but he only say if he not see it, it not happen!&quot; At once the two giants started arguing again when Mardy held up his hand, hollering, &quot;Quiet! Well, I fer one know how useless GMs can be sometimes. So, I'll help ya out.&quot;<br>
<br>
Mard knelt next to the crumpled form on the ground, turning her over gently. His hand stroked the smooth skin of the high elf's face and he laughed aloud, praising Bristlebane for his good fortune.  Not taking his eyes off his prize, he called up to the giants, &quot;I'll give ya four bodies fer this pathetic piece o' meat, fellas,&quot; knowing the giants would be too dumb to realize the worth of their catch. <br>
<br>
&quot;Four?!&quot; exclaimed Giggle, holding up five fingers and jumping up and down. &quot;Sure, Mardy, Sure! Take this one if you want it. I'm hungry!&quot;<br>
